{"parse":{"title":"Sambas Treasure","pageid":41510200,"revid":793775045,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\">Sambas Treasure</th></tr><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Sambas-BM-4.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Sambas-BM-4.JPG\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Sambas-BM-4.JPG/400px-Sambas-BM-4.JPG\" width=\"400\" height=\"300\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Sambas-BM-4.JPG/600px-Sambas-BM-4.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/5/5f/Sambas-BM-4.JPG/800px-Sambas-BM-4.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"4000\" data-file-height=\"3000\" /></a><div>Sambas Treasure as displayed in the British Museum</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Material</th><td>\nGold, Silver and Bronze</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Created</th><td>\n8th-9th Centuries AD</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\" style=\"white-space:nowrap;\">Present location</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/British_Museum\" title=\"British Museum\">British Museum</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/London\" title=\"London\">London</a></td></tr></tbody></table><p>\nThe <b>Sambas Treasure</b> is a hoard of ancient gold and silver buddhist sculptures found near the town of <a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sambas_(town)&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1\" class=\"new\" title=\"Sambas (town) (page does not exist)\">Sambas</a> in west <a href=\"/wiki/Borneo\" title=\"Borneo\">Borneo</a> that now form part of the <a href=\"/wiki/British_Museum\" title=\"British Museum\">British Museum</a>'s collection.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> Dating from 8th-9th centuries AD, they pre-date the coming of Islam to the <a href=\"/wiki/Indonesia\" title=\"Indonesia\">Indonesian</a> archipelago by four centuries and were probably made in <a href=\"/wiki/Java\" title=\"Java\">Java</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#History_of_Buddhism_in_Southeast_Asia\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">History of Buddhism in Southeast Asia</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Discovery_and_ownership\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Discovery and ownership</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#Description\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Description</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Gallery\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">4</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Gallery</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-5\"><a href=\"#Bibliography\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">5</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Bibliography</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-6\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">6</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"History_of_Buddhism_in_Southeast_Asia\">History of Buddhism in Southeast Asia</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sambas_Treasure&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: History of Buddhism in Southeast Asia\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>Until <a href=\"/wiki/Islam\" title=\"Islam\">Islam</a> became the dominant religion in Indonesia in the 13th Century, both <a href=\"/wiki/Buddhism\" title=\"Buddhism\">Buddhism</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Hinduism\" title=\"Hinduism\">Hinduism</a> were adopted from the India subcontinent as the principal local religions. Over time, many  buddhist sculptures were transported to the islands by pilgrims returning from holy sites in eastern India.  These in turn inspired local craftsmen who developed their own styles and traits. The buddhist sculptures from Sambas Treasure was almost certainly made in Java based on artistic models that were developed in eastern <a href=\"/wiki/India\" title=\"India\">India</a> centuries before.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Discovery_and_ownership\">Discovery and ownership</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sambas_Treasure&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Discovery and ownership\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The Sambas Treasure was found in a large earthenware pot on the south-west coast of Borneo sometime during the 1940s. It was then owned by the collector Tan Yeok Seong, a <a href=\"/wiki/Singaporean\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Singaporean\">Singaporean</a> historian of <a href=\"/wiki/Southeast_Asia\" title=\"Southeast Asia\">Southeast Asia</a> and a collector of historical artefacts. The treasure was subsequently bought by the <a href=\"/wiki/Philanthropist\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Philanthropist\">philanthropist</a> PT Brooke Sewell, who donated it to the British Museum in 1956.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Description\">Description</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sambas_Treasure&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: Description\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The hoard is composed of nine gold and silver <a href=\"/wiki/Buddha\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Buddha\">buddha</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Bodhisattva\" title=\"Bodhisattva\">bodhisattva</a> images. The largest figure is approximately 18&#160;cm high and represents a standing Buddha made of sold silver. In addition to the Buddhist sculptures, the treasure includes a bronze <a href=\"/wiki/Incense_burner\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Incense burner\">incense burner</a> in the shape of a house and a silver votive plaque with text in <a href=\"/wiki/Dh%C4%81ra%E1%B9%87%C4%AB\" title=\"Dh\u0101ra\u1e47\u012b\">dh\u0101ra\u1e47\u012b</a>, which was found in the base of the large Buddha figure. The high quality of the craftsmanship and the use of precious metals such as gold and silver suggest they were originally made for an important local dignitary or patron.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Gallery\">Gallery</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sambas_Treasure&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Gallery\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul class=\"gallery mw-gallery-traditional\">\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Sambas-BM-2.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Sambas-BM-2.JPG/90px-Sambas-BM-2.JPG\" width=\"90\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Sambas-BM-2.JPG/135px-Sambas-BM-2.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/7/76/Sambas-BM-2.JPG/180px-Sambas-BM-2.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"3000\" data-file-height=\"4000\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p><a href=\"/wiki/Avalokiteshvara\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Avalokiteshvara\">Avalokiteshvara</a>  figure with ruby in the backplate\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:British_Museum_Asia_8.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/British_Museum_Asia_8.jpg/90px-British_Museum_Asia_8.jpg\" width=\"90\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/British_Museum_Asia_8.jpg/135px-British_Museum_Asia_8.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/8/8f/British_Museum_Asia_8.jpg/180px-British_Museum_Asia_8.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1815\" data-file-height=\"2420\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Silver standing Buddha under a parasol\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:British_Museum_Asia_51.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/British_Museum_Asia_51.jpg/90px-British_Museum_Asia_51.jpg\" width=\"90\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/British_Museum_Asia_51.jpg/135px-British_Museum_Asia_51.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/d/d1/British_Museum_Asia_51.jpg/180px-British_Museum_Asia_51.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1549\" data-file-height=\"2066\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Bronze incense burner in the shape of a house\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:15px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:British_Museum_Asia_9.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/British_Museum_Asia_9.jpg/90px-British_Museum_Asia_9.jpg\" width=\"90\" height=\"120\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/British_Museum_Asia_9.jpg/135px-British_Museum_Asia_9.jpg 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/90/British_Museum_Asia_9.jpg/180px-British_Museum_Asia_9.jpg 2x\" data-file-width=\"1171\" data-file-height=\"1561\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Avalokiteshvara holding a rosary and a book\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:30px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Sambas-BM-3.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Sambas-BM-3.JPG/120px-Sambas-BM-3.JPG\" width=\"120\" height=\"90\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Sambas-BM-3.JPG/180px-Sambas-BM-3.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/1c/Sambas-BM-3.JPG/240px-Sambas-BM-3.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"4000\" data-file-height=\"3000\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Buddha with flaming halo and bodhisattva avalokiteshvara\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n\t\t<li class=\"gallerybox\" style=\"width: 155px\"><div style=\"width: 155px\">\n\t\t\t<div class=\"thumb\" style=\"width: 150px;\"><div style=\"margin:30px auto;\"><a href=\"/wiki/File:Sambas-BM-5.JPG\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Sambas-BM-5.JPG/120px-Sambas-BM-5.JPG\" width=\"120\" height=\"90\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Sambas-BM-5.JPG/180px-Sambas-BM-5.JPG 1.5x, //upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e1/Sambas-BM-5.JPG/240px-Sambas-BM-5.JPG 2x\" data-file-width=\"4000\" data-file-height=\"3000\" /></a></div></div>\n\t\t\t<div class=\"gallerytext\">\n<p>Seated Buddha, <a href=\"/wiki/Padmapani\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Padmapani\">Padmapani</a> and female bodhisattva\n</p>\n\t\t\t</div>\n\t\t</div></li>\n</ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Bibliography\">Bibliography</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sambas_Treasure&amp;action=edit&amp;section=5\" title=\"Edit section: Bibliography\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li>N. Tarling, The Cambridge History of South East Asia (Cambridge University Press, 1992)</li>\n<li>R. Fisher, Buddhist art and architecture (London, Thames &amp; Hudson, 1993)</li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Sambas_Treasure&amp;action=edit&amp;section=6\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/search.aspx?people=136665&amp;peoA=136665-3-7\">British Museum Collection</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://www.khanacademy.org/humanities/art-asia/southeast-asia/maritime-se-asia/a/a-cache-of-buddhist-figures-from-the-sambas-treasure\">\"A Cache of Buddhist figures from the Sambas Treasure\"</a> Khan Academy. Retrieved 2017-08-03.</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n\n<!-- \nNewPP limit report\nParsed by mw2225\nCached time: 20180918153711\nCache expiry: 1900800\nDynamic content: false\nCPU time usa